Sure! 😀 Providers are only concerned with application level state and are connected to the Redux store. Views are unconnected to the store and should only be concerned with view level state isolated to that component (things like toggling a button or in our case, hiding a dropdown). This pattern helps us enforce separation of concerns.

Another reason we can't hide the dropdown on our provider is because we're using refs to invoke methods on the Dropdown component. Refs are destroyed when their children are destroyed, so we have to sync up establishing the ref with ToolbarView's render method instead of ToolbarProvider.

Provider:
```
clearOutputs() {
const { dispatch, id } = this.props;
dispatch(clearOutputs(id));
}
// pass down this method to the view through props
```

View:
```
// define a method called clearOutputs on the class & bind it in the constructor
clearOutputs () {
this.dropdown.hide()
this.props.clearOutputs()
}

render () {
<li onClick={() => this.clearOutputs()} />
}
```

You might want to move all of the content from renderToolbar into the ToolbarView's actual render method since there's no conditional logic. Here, you would want to leave out clearOutputs from the this.props destructuring since we want to invoke the clearOutputs function on the class.

